%N A101042 a(n) is the smallest positive d such that the n-th prime is the smallest prime p for which p+d is also prime.
%C A101042 Except for n=1, A020483(a(n)/2) is the first appearance of the n-th prime. It is conjectured that a(n) always exists. a(386) is the first number which must be above 10^12.
%H A101042 J. K. Andersen, <a href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/primenumbers/message/15641">Prime gaps (not necessarily consecutive)</a>.
